image.altText: a composite of inside the burnt remains of a bondi unit after a fire and the burnt lithium battery

props.synopsis: A fire breaks out inside a North Bondi apartment due to a faulty lithium-ion battery, forcing 18 tenants to quickly evacuate the complex.

title.children: Tourists 'lucky to get out' after fire caused by e-bike battery burns through North Bondi unit

image.altText: A woman puts a sign on her shop window saying closed.

props.synopsis: From trading biscuits for phone chargers to being forced to throw thousands of dollars worth of food and medical supplies, locals tell of the chaos widespread power outages have caused in regional WA.

title.children: 'Really eerie': Residents recount chaos that ensued after outback city was plunged into darkness

image.altText: A screenshot from a satellite video showing a small dot amid streaks of passing debris

props.synopsis: The Australian Space Agency says it monitored the re-entry to make sure it posed "no threat to people or property".

title.children: Failed US Moon lander believed to have burned up after re-entry over Australia

image.altText: A geographical map of Sydney's north with red, yellow and green spots highlighting pollution at certain beaches and pools.

props.synopsis: Beachwatch NSW warns several beaches and pools in Sydney are "likely" to be contaminated after recent heavy rain swept sewage into the waterways.

title.children: Popular Sydney beaches declared unsuitable for swimming due to 'likely' contamination

image.altText: Stephanie Trethewey, Tasmanian Australian of the Year for 2024

props.synopsis: An Australian of the Year finalist divested shares in an abattoir owned by herself and her husband in the wake of "animal welfare issues".

title.children: Australian of the Year finalist denounces 'crazy vegans' after divesting abattoir co-ownership to husband

image.altText: A Caucasian man in a hat sits on a park bench, putting something in the pocketof his light shirt, khaki pants, greenery behind.

props.synopsis: This 64-year-old outback man recently had skin cancer removed from the top of his head.  It is one of hundreds he has had after a youth spent in the sun.

title.children: Growing up, Jim spent his weekends fishing, boating and swimming. Now he is paying for those days

image.altText: A hand holding an air-conditioner remote control.

props.synopsis: Those of us lucky enough to have air conditioning may be tempted to crank it up. An expert in keeping cool says running it at a higher temperature with a fan running is much more energy efficient.

title.children: Blasting your aircon on full bore to beat the humidity? This hybrid method uses 70 per cent less power

image.altText: Mining equipment.

props.synopsis: Problems for Russell Vale coal mine in Wollongong have escalated with the state's Resources Regulator shutting down work on the site because of safety concerns.

title.children: Dozens of workers stood down after coal mine is shut over repeated safety breaches

image.altText: Close up of a hand typing on a keyboard in a dark room

props.synopsis: Credential stuffing has long been used as a form of cyber crime, but a recent rise in attacks has affected thousands of Australians. Here's what credential stuffing is, how it works, and how you can protect yourself.

title.children: Thousands of people have been affected by a jump in credential stuffing attacks. Here's how to tell if you're affected

image.altText: The scene of a car crash at night.

props.synopsis: A 14-year-old Canberra boy who was allegedly driving a stolen car at the time it collided with another vehicle, killing a 19-year-old man and injuring two other boys, is facing charges of culpable driving causing death, driving a motor vehicle without consent, and culpable driving causing grievous bodily harm.

title.children: Fourteen-year-old Canberra boy accused of driving stolen car in crash that killed 'mate' released on bail

image.altText: A children's playground is closed off with gates with a notice attached to the gates.

props.synopsis: It's also been revealed that the New South Wales transport authority was emailed about asbestos in the Rozelle Parklands seven days before testing the site.

title.children: 'It is an emergency': More than 10 tonnes of asbestos waste suspected to be in Rozelle Parklands

image.altText: A sign that says 'no stopping' in the foreground in front of a tall apartment building, Opal Tower.

props.synopsis: Consumers could be forgiven for asking themselves if it is safe to buy an apartment off the plan with issues frequently emerging in Sydney's building developments. But industry stakeholders say new laws protect prospective buyers.

title.children: A litany of building defects across NSW has shaken consumers but experts say new laws are turning things around

image.altText: A broken power transmission tower on farmland

props.synopsis: Power is starting to return to Kalgoorlie-Boulder after a summer storm toppled massive transmission towers, causing extended outages to the city's water, fuel, internet and phone services.

title.children: 'Freak storm' blamed for massive power, water blackouts in WA with massive towers 'crumpled like tin foil'

image.altText: Josh Hazlewood holds the ball up as he leaves the field ahead of his teammates

props.synopsis: Australia makes light work of the West Indies in Adelaide, completing a 10-wicket win before lunch on day three. Follow all the action in our live blog.

title.children: Australia strolls to dominant 10-wicket victory over West Indies in Adelaide

image.altText: Usman Khawaja looks down and touches the side of his face as he walks off the field with a team doctor

props.synopsis: Australia wraps up victory but loses Usman Khawaja to a fearsome bouncer that had the opener spitting blood as he walked off the pitch. Here are five quick hits from day three of the Adelaide Oval Test.

title.children: Five quick hits — Usman's jaw and Hazlewood's haul as Australia wraps up victory on day three

image.altText: A black-and-white archive image of a house.

props.synopsis: One of Alfred Deakin's great-grandchildren has launched a campaign to stop the coastal retreat of Australia's second prime minister from being auctioned off, amid a family dispute over the property's future.

title.children: Australia's second prime minister built this home in 1908. Now his descendants are split on its future

image.altText: Three large rocks sit on the edge of the road.

props.synopsis: The Hepburn Shire Council says the boulders are an interim safety measure after some community members criticised the lack of protection at the Daylesford pub where a car drove into diners.

title.children: Victorian council installs protective boulders outside hotel where crash killed five diners

image.altText: Avoiding handshake

props.synopsis: Reigning women's champion Aryna Sabalenka advances to the fourth round in straight sets as two Aussie men's teams win in the doubles. Follow live.

title.children: Two Aussie teams advance in doubles, Sabalenka and Ukranian avoid handshake after Belarusian dominates

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: 16-year-old Andreeva claws her way back to win third round match

image.altText: A man wearing a blue vest that says UN on it.

props.synopsis: The head of the United Nations agency for Palestinian refugees, Philippe Lazzarini, labels accusations against it a "smear campaign" but commissions an independent review nonetheless.

title.children: UN agency launches review following allegations it has been exploited by Hamas

image.altText: A BOM map of the predicted impact of a cyclone on Far North Queensland

props.synopsis: A tropical low developing in the Coral Sea is forecast to strengthen into a cyclone over the weekend and may track south south-westerly towards the Queensland coast.

title.children: Cyclone track maps could be issued as early as Saturday, as BOM meets with Queensland's disaster committee

image.altText: A Crime Scene Services van on a road in the early hours of the morning.

props.synopsis: Christopher Raftopoulos is accused of attacking five people in four separate incidents in inner Melbourne earlier this month.

title.children: Police can use 'reasonable force' to collect DNA sample from man accused of Melbourne stabbings

image.altText: picture of Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu

props.synopsis: Benjamin Netanyahu rebukes a push to scale back his country's offensive in Gaza, or to help establish a Palestinian state after the war.

title.children: Israel's Netanyahu rejects US calls for Palestinian state after Gaza war, prompting rebuke from White House

image.altText: Nectarines on display in a Coles grocery section. The price displayed is $3.90 per kilogram.

props.synopsis: Queensland Premier Steven Miles says the major supermarkets have agreed to participate in the inquiry. It comes after he met with supermarket executives yesterday.

title.children: Major supermarkets agree to front inquiry into grocery prices as cost of living concerns grow

image.altText: picture of a polar bear on ice

props.synopsis: A study has found that the Greenland ice sheet lost one-fifth more mass than previously estimated, which could have implications for ocean currents that regulate temperatures in Europe and North America.

title.children: NASA scientists surprised by pace of Greenland glacier ice melt

image.altText: A woman looking at a letter.

props.synopsis: Since rebates for psychology sessions were halved a year ago, the cost of living crisis has forced Australians to compromise and even forego critical mental health care.

title.children: Patients struggle to afford psychology appointments after government halves subsidies

image.altText: Smiling girl, brown hair tied back, blue t-shirt, black shorts, purple keds,holds cans in her hand, next to a car

props.synopsis: Emily McLaren needs $12,000 to go to an American space camp. Recycling about 60,000 containers will help her save for half of it.

title.children: With each empty beer bottle and drink can, Emily is 10 cents closer to a space camp in the US

image.altText: Luke Plapp

props.synopsis: Luke Plapp is forced out of the Tour Down Under after the Australian cycling star suffered severe road rash in a crash, while Rudy Molard shares a picture of his injuries from hospital. Warning: graphic images.

title.children: Aussie star out of Tour Down Under after suffering brutal road rash, as French rider shares photo of his horrific injuries

image.altText: Cotton blossoming in a field.

props.synopsis: Singapore-based cotton giant Louis Dreyfus Company is set to acquire 100 per cent of Namoi Cotton shares.

title.children: Australia's oldest and largest cotton company set to transfer into international hands

image.altText: A red panda climbs through a wooden tube.

props.synopsis: The new cub at Altina Wildlife Park near Wagga Wagga is the first born in Australia for two years — and with only 10,000 red pandas left worldwide, breeding programs like it are key to survival of the species.

title.children: There are about 50 red pandas in Australia, but none have successfully given birth in two years — until now

image.altText: A participant stands near a logo of IMF at the International Monetary Fund - World Bank Annual Meeting

props.synopsis: The ASX climbs strongly across most sectors, despite signs of a consumer spending slowdown and an IMF warning that interest rates may need to rise further. Follow the day's events and insights from our business reporters on the ABC News live markets blog.

title.children: IMF warns the Reserve Bank may need to lift interest rates again, ASX records strong gains despite retail worries — as it happened

image.altText: A picture of a baby on a table at a birthday party.

props.synopsis: Hobart mother Maddison Butler should be celebrating her son's first birthday. Instead she is honouring his short life.

title.children: 'Happiest baby' Khaylan remembered at memorial for what should be his first birthday
